": {"begin": 936, "end": 944}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5290"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PI3K", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9933973550796509, "span": {"begin": 983, "end": 987}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrioid", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.44071194529533386, "span": {"begin": 1021, "end": 1033}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018269"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrioid carcinomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999967813491821, "span": {"begin": 1021, "end": 1044}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004714"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "atypical hyperplasia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999926090240479, "span": {"begin": 1070, "end": 1090}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999977350234985, "span": {"begin": 1141, "end": 1146}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9727957844734192, "span": {"begin": 1207, "end": 1210}}, {"id": ["mim:608089", "mesh:D016889"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrial carcinomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999812841415405, "span": {"begin": 1256, "end": 1278}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018269"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrioid cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999701976776123, "span": {"begin": 1351, "end": 1370}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8383366465568542, "span": {"begin": 1386, "end": 1389}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "p53 mutations", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9976423382759094, "span": {"begin": 1386, "end": 1399}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999783039093018, "span": {"begin": 1449, "end": 1454}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4437"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "DNA mismatch repair genes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7611439228057861, "span": {"begin": 1486, "end": 1511}}, {"id": ["mesh:D018269"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrioid carcinomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9988692402839661, "span": {"begin": 1548, "end": 1571}}, {"id": ["mim:608089", "mesh:D016889"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrial carcinomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999998152256012, "span": {"begin": 1611, "end": 1633}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "women", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7359782457351685, "span": {"begin": 1637, "end": 1642}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003123"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HNPCC", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999995231628418, "span": {"begin": 1662, "end": 1667}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003123"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal carcinoma", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999998211860657, "span": {"begin": 1669, "end": 1713}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009369"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999890327453613, "span": {"begin": 1827, "end": 1833}}], "text": "The development of endometrioid adenocarcinoma involves the progressive acquisition of several genetic alterations in tumor suppressor genes and oncogenes (Ellenson et al., 2015). For example, PTEN (phosphatase and tensin homolog) tumor suppressor gene mutations have been identified in 30% to 80% of endometrioid carcinomas and in atypical hyperplasia (more than 20%) [Mutter et al., 2000; Abal et al., 2006; Ellenson et al., 2015]; this may support the fact that atypical hyperplasia may be a precursor of endometrial carcinoma and that PTEN mutation may occur before the development of fully developed cancer (Ellenson et al., 2015). KRAS (Kirsten rat sarcoma virus) activating mutations were seen in 10% to 30% of type I endometrial cancers [Lax et al., 2000; Tashiro et al., 2014]; also mutated KRAS stimulates PI3K/AKT signaling [Ellenson et al., 2015]. PIK3CA(phosphatidylinositol-4,5-biphosphate 3-kinase catalytic subunit), an oncogene that encodes the catalytic subunit of PI3K, is mutated in approximately 40% endometrioid carcinomas. It is rarely mutated in atypical hyperplasia, suggesting that this mutation may play a role in tumor development [Oda et al., 2005; Hayes et al., 2006]. Lastly, p53 is another gene that is mutated (10%-20%) in endometrial carcinomas (Risinger et al., 1992; Kihana et al., 1995). Since well differentiated endometrioid cancer are lacking in p53 mutations, these mutations are thought to be late event in tumor progression. Defects involving DNA mismatch repair genes are found in about 30%-40% sporadic endometrioid carcinomas and they are particularly prevalent in endometrial carcinomas in women from families with HNPCC (hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal carcinoma). This defect leads to a mutator phenotype, leading to more rapid accumulation of mutations in genes involved in cancer development (Esteller et al., 1999).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:08:32 +0000 2026"}